ce:section.ce:para:
Gut microbiome is a complex eco-system and consists of a vast quantity of microorganisms (Cresci and Izzo, 2019). These microorganisms include bacteria, viruses, archaea, fungi and protozoa (Rinninella et al., 2019). The human GIT hosts trillions of microorganisms some of which are either advantageous or injurious to the health. Further, human gut microbiome exhibits huge diversity and it may consists of nearly 500–1000 bacterial species (Rinninella et al., 2019). These bacterial species are comprised of around 1800 genera (Johnson, 2020). It is estimated that the overall gut microbiome composed of 3.3 million gene which is 150 times higher than human genome and therefore contribute to diverse biochemical and metabolic activities that potentially affects the human health Fig. 3
                      (Tsiaoussis et al., 2019). Human microbiome contains both gram positive and gram negative bacterial strains. In case of gram negative bacterial community, Bacteroides or Prevotella species are known to be dominating (~90%) whereas in case of gram positive, Clostridium and Lactobacillus are found as the majority belonging to the phylum Firmicutes (Ruan et al., 2020). Further, nearly 97% of gut microbes are anaerobic in nature where fungi and archaea contribute ~1% of the overall intestinal microbiome (Gangadoo et al., 2021). The abundance of microbiome gradually increases along the GIT and therefore found to be significantly higher in colon. Though, most of the microbiome is favorable and exhibits symbiotic relationship with the host, if the composition and metabolic activities are perturbed, it may result in to unpleasant circumstances to the body (Durack and Lynch, 2019). Further, preconditions for various diseases may arise and sometimes it can be appeared as cancers, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, depression and disorders in immunity (Wang et al., 2017). Microbiome plays a crucial role in the overall immune system and help to absorb nutrients from the food which are indigestible to the body. Further, it has been reported that, ~80% microbiome in fecal sample of a healthy adult is mainly contributed by phyla including Actinobacteria, Bacteroidetes and Firmicutes (Ghebretatios et al., 2021). Change in relative ratio of Firmicutes/Bacteroidetes (F/B) is directly related to the physical status of GIT, wherein a higher or lower ration of F/B is known as dysbiosis. An increased value of F/B ratio may be seen in terms of obesity while decreased value may appear as inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) (Stojanov et al., 2020). In addition, there are several environmental factors which exert a significant effect to modulate gut microbiome. These factors may include diet, drugs, toxins and pathogens (Hasan and Yang, 2019). Among numerous factors, exposure of nanoparticles (organic/inorganic) which are found in various products along with their vast existence in the environment may lead beneficial or harmful effects to the GIT microbial community (Campos et al., 2022). These nanoparticles may possibly be consumed through the inhalation and/or oral route intentionally or unintentionally reach to the GIT and thereafter interacts with the microbiome (Bouwmeester et al., 2018). The interaction of nanoparticles with microbiome not only alters the microbial diversity/abundance but also influences the intestinal environment (Lamas et al., 2020; Bergin and Witzmann, 2013; Chen et al., 2022). On the other hand, interaction of nanoparticles with intestinal environment can also make a significant impact to alter the microbial diversity and their community (Qiu et al., 2018). Thus, owing to the vast exposure of GBNMs and their consequences on the human heath which may possibly be originated from the altered microbiome should be carefully analyzed (Ding et al., 2022) (Fig. 4
                     ).
